{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e346b50c-cd25-4288-9d03-958fc24e1d34","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, aligning them with your new SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** only **reinstalls** the currently-installed versions to fix corrupted files — it won't upgrade anything.\n\nQuick steps:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still see errors after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) appears, and reinstall any missing workloads with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ac6135e-20d6-4732-8279-34358ed7a609","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a .NET SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads. Use this when you've updated the SDK and need workloads to match.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but doesn't upgrade them.\n\nAfter an SDK update, the right choice is `dotnet workload update`.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"77CE:1B9BC9:8194544:8FB5461:69EABD7B"},"id":"980bc5b3-2d98-4bce-9ce8-0573d42c973a","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:46:59.996Z","parentId":"5e8bf942-4bb6-4370-af85-9f14dab7fdf4"}
